<body>

<p class="section-label">Auth Architecture Deep Dive</p>
<h1>How to Build a Secure Auth System in Next.js 15 From Scratch</h1>
<p class="subtitle">A plain, step-by-step guide to authentication using httpOnly cookies, a BFF proxy, TanStack Query, Zod, and React Hook Form. Written for any engineer who wants to understand and implement it.</p>

<hr>

<p>
Authentication is one of the most misunderstood parts of building a web app. It looks simple until you start asking questions like: where do I store the token? How do I refresh it silently? What happens if two requests expire at the same time? How do I prevent CSRF?
</p>
<p>
This article walks through a complete, production-ready auth system built on Next.js 15. We will cover every layer: the browser client, the server-side proxy, cookie management, token rotation, form validation, and session state. You will see the actual code and understand why each decision was made.
</p>
<p>
The flows covered are: signup, email verification, login, silent token refresh, and logout.
</p>

<hr>

<h2>The Architecture at a Glance</h2>

<p>The entire system is built around one principle: <strong>the browser should never have direct access to auth tokens.</strong> To enforce this, every API request goes through a server-side proxy instead of hitting the real API directly.</p>

<p>Here are the five layers:</p>

<div class="flow-diagram">
Browser (React Client Components)<br>
&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;| calls service functions<br>
Service Layer  (features/auth/services/auth.service.js)<br>
&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;| uses $apiClient to call<br>
BFF Proxy Route  (app/api/proxy/[...path]/route.js)  -- runs on the server<br>
&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;| uses $apiServer to call<br>
Real Backend API  (https://api.yourapp.com)<br>
&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;^<br>
Session Cookies  (lib/server/session-cookies.js)  -- httpOnly, server-only
</div>

<p>The BFF ("Backend For Frontend") proxy is the critical piece. It sits between the browser and the real API. It reads and writes tokens as httpOnly cookies. It rotates expired access tokens automatically. The browser only ever sees a <code>/api/proxy/...</code> route and a success or error response. It never sees raw JWT values.</p>

<div class="callout-warn">
<strong>Why not store tokens in localStorage?</strong> localStorage is readable by any JavaScript on the page, including injected scripts from an XSS attack. An httpOnly cookie cannot be read by JavaScript at all, even from your own code. This one flag eliminates an entire class of token theft attacks.
</div>

<hr>

<h2>Layer 1: The API Client</h2>

<p>All browser-side API calls go through a single <code>$apiClient</code> object. Here is the full implementation:</p>

<pre><span class="cm">// lib/api/client.js</span>
<span class="kw">import</span> { ApiClientError } <span class="kw">from</span> <span class="str">"@/lib/errors"</span>;
<span class="kw">import</span> { parseFetchResponse } <span class="kw">from</span> <span class="str">"./parse-response"</span>;

<span class="kw">const</span> <span class="vr">BFF</span> = <span class="str">"/api/proxy"</span>;

<span class="kw">async function</span> <span class="fn">send</span>(path, method, body, opts = {}) {
  <span class="kw">const</span> { signal, params } = opts;

  <span class="kw">let</span> url = <span class="str">`${BFF}${path}`</span>;
  <span class="kw">if</span> (params &amp;&amp; Object.keys(params).length &gt; 0) {
    url += <span class="str">`?${new URLSearchParams(params)}`</span>;
  }

  <span class="kw">const</span> headers = <span class="kw">new</span> <span class="tp">Headers</span>({
    <span class="str">Accept</span>: <span class="str">"application/json"</span>,
    <span class="str">"x-csrf"</span>: <span class="str">"1"</span>,
  });
  <span class="kw">if</span> (body !== undefined) headers.<span class="fn">set</span>(<span class="str">"Content-Type"</span>, <span class="str">"application/json"</span>);

  <span class="kw">const</span> response = <span class="kw">await</span> <span class="fn">fetch</span>(url, {
    method,
    headers,
    body: body !== undefined ? <span class="tp">JSON</span>.<span class="fn">stringify</span>(body) : undefined,
    credentials: <span class="str">"include"</span>,
    signal,
  });

  <span class="kw">return</span> <span class="fn">parseFetchResponse</span>(response, {
    throwError: ({ message, status, data }) =&gt; {
      <span class="kw">throw new</span> <span class="tp">ApiClientError</span>({ message, status, data });
    },
  });
}

<span class="kw">export const</span> $apiClient = {
  get:    (path, opts)       =&gt; <span class="fn">send</span>(path, <span class="str">"GET"</span>,    undefined, opts),
  post:   (path, body, opts) =&gt; <span class="fn">send</span>(path, <span class="str">"POST"</span>,   body,      opts),
  put:    (path, body, opts) =&gt; <span class="fn">send</span>(path, <span class="str">"PUT"</span>,    body,      opts),
  patch:  (path, body, opts) =&gt; <span class="fn">send</span>(path, <span class="str">"PATCH"</span>,  body,      opts),
  delete: (path, opts)       =&gt; <span class="fn">send</span>(path, <span class="str">"DELETE"</span>, undefined, opts),
};</pre>

<p>Three things to pay attention to:</p>

<ul>
  <li><strong><code>credentials: "include"</code></strong> tells the browser to attach cookies on every request, including same-origin ones. Without this flag, your auth cookies never travel with the request.</li>
  <li><strong><code>"x-csrf": "1"</code></strong> is a custom CSRF header. The proxy checks for this on every write request (POST, PUT, PATCH, DELETE). An attacker cannot set custom headers on cross-origin requests, so this header is proof the request came from your own app.</li>
  <li><strong>All calls go to <code>/api/proxy</code></strong>, never directly to the real API. The real API URL is a server-only secret.</li>
</ul>

<hr>

<h2>Layer 2: The BFF Proxy</h2>

<p>This is the most important file in the auth system. It runs on the server. Every request passes through it.</p>

<h3>The Dispatcher</h3>

<p>The dispatcher reads the incoming path and decides which handler to call:</p>

<pre><span class="cm">// app/api/proxy/[...path]/route.js</span>
<span class="kw">async function</span> <span class="fn">dispatch</span>(req, ctx, method) {
  <span class="cm">// Reject any mutating request that is missing the CSRF header</span>
  <span class="kw">if</span> (MUTATING.<span class="fn">has</span>(method) &amp;&amp; req.headers?.<span class="fn">get</span>?.(<span class="str">"x-csrf"</span>) !== <span class="str">"1"</span>) {
    <span class="kw">return</span> <span class="fn">fail</span>({ message: <span class="str">"Forbidden"</span> }, 403);
  }

  <span class="kw">const</span> path = (<span class="kw">await</span> ctx?.params)?.path ?? [];
  <span class="kw">const</span> upstreamPath = <span class="str">"/"</span> + path?.<span class="fn">join</span>?.(<span class="str">"/"</span>) + <span class="kw">new</span> <span class="tp">URL</span>(req?.url).search;
  <span class="kw">const</span> body = <span class="kw">await</span> <span class="fn">readBody</span>(req, method);

  <span class="kw">if</span> (upstreamPath?.<span class="fn">startsWith</span>?(AUTH_API_PATHS?.LOGIN))
    <span class="kw">return</span> <span class="fn">openSession</span>(upstreamPath, method, body);

  <span class="kw">if</span> (upstreamPath?.<span class="fn">startsWith</span>?(AUTH_API_PATHS?.VERIFY_EMAIL))
    <span class="kw">return</span> <span class="fn">openSession</span>(upstreamPath, method, body);

  <span class="kw">if</span> (upstreamPath?.<span class="fn">startsWith</span>?(AUTH_API_PATHS?.LOGOUT))
    <span class="kw">return</span> <span class="fn">closeSession</span>();

  <span class="cm">// All other requests (including signup) are proxied without special handling</span>
  <span class="kw">return</span> <span class="fn">proxyRequest</span>(upstreamPath, method, body);
}</pre>

<p>The logic is straightforward. Login and email verification both result in a session being opened (tokens written). Logout closes the session (tokens cleared). Everything else, including signup, is just forwarded to the real API as-is. Signup does not write any cookies because the user has not verified their identity yet.</p>

<h3>Opening a Session</h3>

<pre><span class="kw">async function</span> <span class="fn">openSession</span>(path, method, body) {
  <span class="kw">try</span> {
    <span class="kw">const</span> result = <span class="kw">await</span> <span class="fn">$apiServer</span>(path, { method, body });
    <span class="kw">const</span> tokens = result?.data?.data ?? result?.data;

    <span class="cm">// Write tokens into httpOnly cookies. The browser never sees the raw values.</span>
    <span class="kw">await</span> <span class="fn">writeSessionCookies</span>({
      accessToken:  tokens?.accessToken,
      refreshToken: tokens?.refreshToken,
    });

    <span class="cm">// Return a plain success response. No token values in the body.</span>
    <span class="kw">return</span> <span class="fn">success</span>();
  } <span class="kw">catch</span> (e) {
    <span class="kw">return</span> <span class="fn">rejectWith</span>(e);
  }
}</pre>

<p>The backend returns <code>{ accessToken, refreshToken }</code> in the response body. The proxy intercepts that, writes both values into httpOnly cookies, and sends a plain <code>{ ok: true }</code> back to the browser. The browser gets confirmation that login worked, but it never receives the actual tokens.</p>

<h3>Authenticated Proxy With Silent Token Rotation</h3>

<p>This handler covers every request that needs to carry an access token. It also handles automatic token rotation when a token expires:</p>

<pre><span class="kw">async function</span> <span class="fn">proxyRequest</span>(path, method, body) {
  <span class="kw">const</span> accessToken = <span class="kw">await</span> <span class="fn">readAccessToken</span>(); <span class="cm">// read from httpOnly cookie</span>

  <span class="kw">try</span> {
    <span class="cm">// First attempt with the current access token</span>
    <span class="kw">const</span> result = <span class="kw">await</span> <span class="fn">$apiServer</span>(path, { method, body, accessToken });
    <span class="kw">return</span> <span class="fn">resolveWith</span>(result);
  } <span class="kw">catch</span> (e) {
    <span class="cm">// Only handle 401. Anything else is a real error.</span>
    <span class="kw">if</span> (!(e <span class="kw">instanceof</span> <span class="tp">ApiServerError</span>) || e?.status !== 401)
      <span class="kw">return</span> <span class="fn">rejectWith</span>(e);

    <span class="cm">// Try to get a fresh access token using the refresh token</span>
    <span class="kw">const</span> freshToken = <span class="kw">await</span> <span class="fn">rotateTokens</span>();

    <span class="kw">if</span> (!freshToken) {
      <span class="cm">// Refresh token is also expired. Session is dead. Clear cookies.</span>
      <span class="kw">await</span> <span class="fn">clearSessionCookies</span>();
      <span class="kw">return</span> <span class="fn">rejectWith</span>(e);
    }

    <span class="kw">try</span> {
      <span class="cm">// Retry the original request with the fresh token</span>
      <span class="kw">const</span> retried = <span class="kw">await</span> <span class="fn">$apiServer</span>(path, { method, body, accessToken: freshToken });
      <span class="kw">return</span> <span class="fn">resolveWith</span>(retried);
    } <span class="kw">catch</span> (retryErr) {
      <span class="kw">return</span> <span class="fn">rejectWith</span>(retryErr);
    }
  }
}</pre>

<p>The flow is: try the request, if it returns 401 try to refresh, if refresh works retry the original request, if refresh fails kill the session. The user experiences none of this. Their request just works, or they get silently redirected to the login page.</p>

<h3>Token Rotation With Deduplication</h3>

<pre><span class="cm">// Only one refresh call runs at a time, even if multiple requests expire simultaneously</span>
<span class="kw">let</span> rotating = <span class="kw">null</span>;

<span class="kw">async function</span> <span class="fn">rotateTokens</span>() {
  rotating ??= <span class="fn">doRotate</span>().<span class="fn">finally</span>(() =&gt; { rotating = <span class="kw">null</span>; });
  <span class="kw">return</span> rotating;
}

<span class="kw">async function</span> <span class="fn">doRotate</span>() {
  <span class="kw">const</span> refreshToken = <span class="kw">await</span> <span class="fn">readRefreshToken</span>();
  <span class="kw">if</span> (!refreshToken) <span class="kw">return null</span>;

  <span class="kw">try</span> {
    <span class="kw">const</span> result = <span class="kw">await</span> <span class="fn">$apiServer</span>(AUTH_API_PATHS?.REFRESH, {
      method: <span class="str">"POST"</span>,
      body: { refreshToken },
    });
    <span class="kw">const</span> tokens = result?.data?.data ?? result?.data;
    <span class="kw">if</span> (!tokens?.accessToken) <span class="kw">return null</span>;

    <span class="kw">await</span> <span class="fn">writeSessionCookies</span>({
      accessToken:  tokens?.accessToken,
      refreshToken: tokens?.refreshToken ?? refreshToken,
    });
    <span class="kw">return</span> tokens?.accessToken;
  } <span class="kw">catch</span> {
    <span class="kw">return null</span>;
  }
}</pre>

<div class="callout">
<strong>Why the deduplication?</strong> Imagine the user has three browser tabs open. All three make API requests at the same moment, and all three get a 401 because the access token just expired. Without deduplication, you would fire three separate refresh requests. The second and third would fail because refresh tokens are often single-use. With the <code>rotating ??= ...</code> pattern, all three calls share the same Promise. Only one refresh request hits the backend. The other two wait and reuse the result.
</div>

<h3>Closing a Session</h3>

<pre><span class="kw">async function</span> <span class="fn">closeSession</span>() {
  <span class="kw">const</span> refreshToken = <span class="kw">await</span> <span class="fn">readRefreshToken</span>();
  <span class="kw">try</span> {
    <span class="kw">if</span> (refreshToken) {
      <span class="cm">// Tell the backend to invalidate the refresh token</span>
      <span class="kw">await</span> <span class="fn">$apiServer</span>(AUTH_API_PATHS?.LOGOUT, {
        method: <span class="str">"POST"</span>,
        body: { refreshToken },
      });
    }
  } <span class="kw">catch</span> {
    <span class="cm">// Best effort. Cookies are always cleared regardless.</span>
  }
  <span class="kw">await</span> <span class="fn">clearSessionCookies</span>();
  <span class="kw">return</span> <span class="fn">success</span>();
}</pre>

<p>The <code>try/catch</code> around the backend logout call is intentional. If the API is unreachable, the user should still be logged out on the client side. Cookies are always cleared, no matter what the backend says.</p>

<hr>

<h2>Layer 3: Session Cookies</h2>

<p>This file is marked <code>"server-only"</code>. If you accidentally import it inside a client component, Next.js will throw a build error. That is the point.</p>

<pre><span class="kw">import</span> <span class="str">"server-only"</span>;
<span class="kw">import</span> { cookies } <span class="kw">from</span> <span class="str">"next/headers"</span>;

<span class="kw">const</span> ACCESS_COOKIE_MAX_AGE  = 60 * 60;           <span class="cm">// 1 hour</span>
<span class="kw">const</span> REFRESH_COOKIE_MAX_AGE = 60 * 60 * 24 * 14; <span class="cm">// 14 days</span>

<span class="kw">function</span> <span class="fn">cookieBase</span>() {
  <span class="kw">const</span> isProd = process.env.NODE_ENV === <span class="str">"production"</span>;
  <span class="kw">return</span> {
    secure:   isProd,
    sameSite: <span class="str">"lax"</span>,
    path:     <span class="str">"/"</span>,
  };
}

<span class="kw">export async function</span> <span class="fn">writeSessionCookies</span>({ accessToken, refreshToken }) {
  <span class="kw">const</span> store = <span class="kw">await</span> <span class="fn">cookies</span>();

  <span class="kw">if</span> (accessToken) {
    store.<span class="fn">set</span>({
      ...<span class="fn">cookieBase</span>(),
      httpOnly: <span class="kw">true</span>,
      name:     <span class="str">"app_at"</span>,
      value:    accessToken,
      maxAge:   ACCESS_COOKIE_MAX_AGE,
    });
  }
  <span class="kw">if</span> (refreshToken) {
    store.<span class="fn">set</span>({
      ...<span class="fn">cookieBase</span>(),
      httpOnly: <span class="kw">true</span>,
      name:     <span class="str">"app_rt"</span>,
      value:    refreshToken,
      maxAge:   REFRESH_COOKIE_MAX_AGE,
    });
  }
}

<span class="kw">export async function</span> <span class="fn">clearSessionCookies</span>() {
  <span class="kw">const</span> store = <span class="kw">await</span> <span class="fn">cookies</span>();
  store.<span class="fn">set</span>({ ...<span class="fn">cookieBase</span>(), httpOnly: <span class="kw">true</span>, name: <span class="str">"app_at"</span>, value: <span class="str">""</span>, maxAge: 0 });
  store.<span class="fn">set</span>({ ...<span class="fn">cookieBase</span>(), httpOnly: <span class="kw">true</span>, name: <span class="str">"app_rt"</span>, value: <span class="str">""</span>, maxAge: 0 });
}</pre>

<p>The cookie flags explained:</p>

<ul>
  <li><strong><code>httpOnly: true</code></strong> is the most important one. It makes the cookie completely invisible to JavaScript. No code running in the browser can read, modify, or steal it.</li>
  <li><strong><code>secure: isProd</code></strong> means the cookie is only sent over HTTPS in production. This allows local development over plain HTTP without hassle.</li>
  <li><strong><code>sameSite: "lax"</code></strong> means the cookie is not sent with cross-origin POST requests, which is how CSRF attacks work. It is still sent when a user navigates to your site by clicking a link from another site.</li>
  <li><strong><code>maxAge</code></strong> is a cleanup upper bound. The real expiry is enforced by the backend via the JWT <code>exp</code> claim. The cookie maxAge just ensures dead values do not sit in the browser forever.</li>
</ul>

<hr>

<h2>Layer 4: The Service Layer</h2>

<p>Service functions are simple. Each one makes a single API call and normalises the error. They know nothing about UI, toasts, or redirects.</p>

<pre><span class="cm">// features/auth/services/auth.service.js</span>
<span class="kw">import</span> { $apiClient } <span class="kw">from</span> <span class="str">"@/lib/api/client"</span>;
<span class="kw">import</span> { ApiClientError, normalizeApiClientError } <span class="kw">from</span> <span class="str">"@/lib/errors"</span>;
<span class="kw">import</span> { AUTH_API_PATHS } <span class="kw">from</span> <span class="str">"../constants"</span>;

<span class="kw">export async function</span> <span class="fn">login</span>(credentials) {
  <span class="kw">try</span> {
    <span class="kw">const</span> result = <span class="kw">await</span> $apiClient.<span class="fn">post</span>(AUTH_API_PATHS.LOGIN, credentials);
    <span class="kw">return</span> result.data?.data ?? result.data;
  } <span class="kw">catch</span> (e) {
    <span class="kw">throw</span> <span class="fn">normalizeApiClientError</span>(e);
  }
}

<span class="kw">export async function</span> <span class="fn">signup</span>(data) {
  <span class="kw">try</span> {
    <span class="kw">const</span> result = <span class="kw">await</span> $apiClient.<span class="fn">post</span>(AUTH_API_PATHS.SIGNUP, data);
    <span class="kw">return</span> result.data?.data ?? result.data;
  } <span class="kw">catch</span> (e) {
    <span class="kw">throw</span> <span class="fn">normalizeApiClientError</span>(e);
  }
}

<span class="kw">export async function</span> <span class="fn">logout</span>() {
  <span class="kw">await</span> $apiClient.<span class="fn">post</span>(AUTH_API_PATHS.LOGOUT);
}

<span class="kw">export async function</span> <span class="fn">verifyEmail</span>({ token }) {
  <span class="kw">try</span> {
    <span class="kw">const</span> result = <span class="kw">await</span> $apiClient.<span class="fn">post</span>(AUTH_API_PATHS.VERIFY_EMAIL, { token });
    <span class="kw">return</span> result.data?.data ?? result.data;
  } <span class="kw">catch</span> (e) {
    <span class="kw">throw</span> <span class="fn">normalizeApiClientError</span>(e);
  }
}

<span class="kw">export async function</span> <span class="fn">getMe</span>() {
  <span class="kw">try</span> {
    <span class="kw">const</span> result = <span class="kw">await</span> $apiClient.<span class="fn">get</span>(AUTH_API_PATHS.ME);
    <span class="kw">return</span> result.data?.data ?? result.data;
  } <span class="kw">catch</span> (e) {
    <span class="cm">// 401 means no session. Return null instead of throwing.</span>
    <span class="kw">if</span> (e <span class="kw">instanceof</span> <span class="tp">ApiClientError</span> &amp;&amp; e.status === 401) <span class="kw">return null</span>;
    <span class="kw">throw</span> <span class="fn">normalizeApiClientError</span>(e);
  }
}</pre>

<p><code>getMe()</code> is worth highlighting. It returns <code>null</code> on a 401 instead of throwing. This is because <code>getMe()</code> is used to check whether someone is logged in. If they are not, <code>null</code> is the correct answer. An exception would bubble up through TanStack Query and be treated as an error, which is not what you want for a simple "are you logged in?" check.</p>

<hr>

<h2>Layer 5: TanStack Query Hooks</h2>

<p>Query hooks are where the UI concerns live: toasts, redirects, and cache management. The service functions are pure. The hooks are what connect them to the user experience.</p>

<h3>useMe: Knowing Who Is Logged In</h3>

<pre><span class="kw">export function</span> <span class="fn">useMe</span>(options = {}) {
  <span class="kw">return</span> <span class="fn">useQuery</span>({
    queryKey: AUTH_QUERY_KEYS.<span class="fn">me</span>(),
    queryFn:  getMe,
    staleTime: STALE_TIMES.USER_SESSION,
    ...options,
  });
}</pre>

<p>Any component that needs to know the current user calls <code>useAuthUser()</code>, which is a thin wrapper over <code>useMe()</code>:</p>

<pre><span class="kw">export function</span> <span class="fn">useAuthUser</span>() {
  <span class="kw">const</span> { data, isLoading, isError, error } = <span class="fn">useMe</span>();
  <span class="kw">return</span> {
    user:               data ?? <span class="kw">null</span>,
    activeOrganisation: data?.activeOrganisation ?? <span class="kw">null</span>,
    isLoading,
    isError,
    error,
  };
}</pre>

<p>Components import from <code>useAuthUser</code>, not from <code>useMe</code> directly. This keeps the query layer as an internal detail and gives you one place to change the shape of user data if the API changes.</p>

<h3>useLogin</h3>

<pre><span class="kw">export function</span> <span class="fn">useLogin</span>() {
  <span class="kw">const</span> router = <span class="fn">useRouter</span>();
  <span class="kw">const</span> qc = <span class="fn">useQueryClient</span>();

  <span class="kw">return</span> <span class="fn">useMutation</span>({
    mutationFn: login,
    onSuccess: (data) =&gt; {
      <span class="fn">toastSuccess</span>(data?.message || <span class="str">"Welcome back!"</span>);
      qc.<span class="fn">removeQueries</span>({ queryKey: AUTH_QUERY_KEYS.<span class="fn">me</span>() }); <span class="cm">// clear any stale user cache</span>
      router.<span class="fn">refresh</span>();                                        <span class="cm">// re-run server components</span>
      router.<span class="fn">replace</span>(AUTH_REDIRECTS.DASHBOARD_HOME_PAGE);
    },
    onError: (error) =&gt; {
      <span class="cm">// Validation errors show inline under form fields. No toast needed for those.</span>
      <span class="kw">if</span> (error.code !== ERROR_CODES.VALIDATION) {
        <span class="fn">toastError</span>(error.message);
      }
    },
  });
}</pre>

<p>The <code>router.refresh()</code> call is easy to overlook but important. After login, cookies exist that did not before. <code>router.refresh()</code> tells Next.js to re-run all server components for the current route. Without it, any server component that reads session data would still see the pre-login state.</p>

<h3>useSignup</h3>

<pre><span class="kw">export function</span> <span class="fn">useSignup</span>() {
  <span class="kw">const</span> router = <span class="fn">useRouter</span>();
  <span class="kw">const</span> qc = <span class="fn">useQueryClient</span>();

  <span class="kw">return</span> <span class="fn">useMutation</span>({
    mutationFn: signup,
    onSuccess: (data, variables) =&gt; {
      <span class="fn">toastSuccess</span>(data?.message || <span class="str">"Account created! Check your inbox."</span>);
      qc.<span class="fn">removeQueries</span>({ queryKey: AUTH_QUERY_KEYS.<span class="fn">me</span>() });

      <span class="cm">// Start the cooldown so the resend button is locked on the next page</span>
      localStorage.<span class="fn">setItem</span>(<span class="str">"app_verify_cooldown"</span>, <span class="tp">String</span>(<span class="tp">Date</span>.<span class="fn">now</span>()));

      <span class="cm">// Pass the email via the URL so the verify-email page can display it</span>
      <span class="kw">const</span> email = <span class="fn">encodeURIComponent</span>(variables.email);
      router.<span class="fn">refresh</span>();
      router.<span class="fn">replace</span>(<span class="str">`/verify-email?email=${email}`</span>);
    },
    onError: (error) =&gt; {
      <span class="kw">if</span> (error.code !== ERROR_CODES.VALIDATION) <span class="fn">toastError</span>(error.message);
    },
  });
}</pre>

<h3>useLogout: Always Run the Cleanup</h3>

<pre><span class="kw">export function</span> <span class="fn">useLogout</span>() {
  <span class="kw">const</span> router = <span class="fn">useRouter</span>();
  <span class="kw">const</span> qc = <span class="fn">useQueryClient</span>();

  <span class="kw">return</span> <span class="fn">useMutation</span>({
    mutationFn: logout,
    onSuccess: () =&gt; <span class="fn">toastSuccess</span>(<span class="str">"Signed out successfully."</span>),
    onError:   () =&gt; <span class="fn">toastError</span>(<span class="str">"Sign out failed. Redirecting for security."</span>),
    <span class="cm">// onSettled runs whether the call succeeded or failed</span>
    onSettled: () =&gt; {
      qc.<span class="fn">clear</span>();
      router.<span class="fn">refresh</span>();
      router.<span class="fn">replace</span>(<span class="str">"/login"</span>);
    },
  });
}</pre>

<div class="callout-tip">
<strong>onSettled vs onSuccess for logout.</strong> If you put the redirect in <code>onSuccess</code>, a network error during logout would leave the user stuck on the dashboard with a stale session in memory, even though their cookies might be partially cleared. <code>onSettled</code> always runs, success or failure. Logout should always result in the user being sent to the login page.
</div>

<hr>

<h2>The Error System</h2>

<p>A consistent error class is what allows hooks to decide: show a toast, or show inline field errors? Here is the error class and the utility that maps server errors onto form fields:</p>

<pre><span class="cm">// lib/errors/index.js</span>
<span class="kw">export const</span> ERROR_CODES = Object.freeze({
  NETWORK:           <span class="str">"NETWORK"</span>,
  UNAUTHORIZED:      <span class="str">"UNAUTHORIZED"</span>,
  VALIDATION:        <span class="str">"VALIDATION"</span>,   <span class="cm">// 400 / 422</span>
  TOO_MANY_REQUESTS: <span class="str">"TOO_MANY_REQUESTS"</span>,
  SERVER:            <span class="str">"SERVER"</span>,
  UNKNOWN:           <span class="str">"UNKNOWN"</span>,
});

<span class="kw">export class</span> <span class="tp">ApiClientError</span> <span class="kw">extends</span> <span class="tp">Error</span> {
  <span class="fn">constructor</span>({ message, status, data, fieldErrors } = {}) {
    <span class="kw">const</span> raw = message ?? data?.message ?? data?.error ?? <span class="kw">null</span>;
    <span class="kw">super</span>(<span class="fn">sanitizeMessage</span>(raw));
    <span class="kw">this</span>.status      = status ?? 0;
    <span class="kw">this</span>.code        = <span class="fn">codeFromStatus</span>(<span class="kw">this</span>.status);
    <span class="kw">this</span>.fieldErrors = fieldErrors ?? (
      data?.errors &amp;&amp; <span class="kw">typeof</span> data.errors === <span class="str">"object"</span> ? data.errors : <span class="kw">null</span>
    );
  }
}

<span class="cm">// Puts server-side field errors directly onto react-hook-form fields</span>
<span class="kw">export function</span> <span class="fn">applyServerErrors</span>(error, setError) {
  <span class="kw">if</span> (!error?.fieldErrors) <span class="kw">return</span>;
  <span class="kw">for</span> (<span class="kw">const</span> [field, message] <span class="kw">of</span> Object.<span class="fn">entries</span>(error.fieldErrors)) {
    <span class="fn">setError</span>(field, { type: <span class="str">"server"</span>, message });
  }
}</pre>

<p>If the API returns <code>{ errors: { email: "This email is already taken" } }</code>, calling <code>applyServerErrors(error, setError)</code> automatically renders that message under the email field. You do not need to write any mapping code in your forms.</p>

<hr>

<h2>Form Validation With Zod</h2>

<p>Every form has a Zod schema. The schema validates on the client before anything is sent to the server. Here are the schemas used in the auth flows:</p>

<pre><span class="kw">import</span> { z } <span class="kw">from</span> <span class="str">"zod"</span>;

<span class="cm">// Reusable password rule set</span>
<span class="kw">const</span> passwordSchema = z
  .<span class="fn">string</span>()
  .<span class="fn">min</span>(8,   <span class="str">"Password must be at least 8 characters"</span>)
  .<span class="fn">max</span>(128, <span class="str">"Password is too long"</span>)
  .<span class="fn">regex</span>(/[A-Z]/,       <span class="str">"Must contain at least one uppercase letter"</span>)
  .<span class="fn">regex</span>(/[a-z]/,       <span class="str">"Must contain at least one lowercase letter"</span>)
  .<span class="fn">regex</span>(/[0-9]/,       <span class="str">"Must contain at least one number"</span>)
  .<span class="fn">regex</span>(/[^A-Za-z0-9]/, <span class="str">"Must contain at least one special character"</span>);

<span class="kw">export const</span> signupSchema = z.<span class="fn">object</span>({
  firstName:   z.<span class="fn">string</span>().<span class="fn">trim</span>().<span class="fn">min</span>(1, <span class="str">"First name is required"</span>).<span class="fn">max</span>(50),
  lastName:    z.<span class="fn">string</span>().<span class="fn">trim</span>().<span class="fn">min</span>(1, <span class="str">"Last name is required"</span>).<span class="fn">max</span>(50),
  email:       z.<span class="fn">string</span>().<span class="fn">trim</span>().<span class="fn">toLowerCase</span>().<span class="fn">email</span>(<span class="str">"Enter a valid email address"</span>),
  password:    passwordSchema,
  acceptTerms: z.<span class="fn">boolean</span>().<span class="fn">refine</span>((v) =&gt; v === <span class="kw">true</span>, <span class="str">"You must accept the Terms and Privacy Policy"</span>),
});

<span class="kw">export const</span> loginSchema = z.<span class="fn">object</span>({
  email:    z.<span class="fn">string</span>().<span class="fn">trim</span>().<span class="fn">toLowerCase</span>().<span class="fn">email</span>(<span class="str">"Enter a valid email address"</span>),
  password: z.<span class="fn">string</span>().<span class="fn">min</span>(1, <span class="str">"Password is required"</span>),
});</pre>

<p>Zod schemas integrate directly with React Hook Form via <code>zodResolver</code>:</p>

<pre><span class="kw">const</span> { register, handleSubmit, formState: { errors }, setError } = <span class="fn">useForm</span>({
  resolver:      <span class="fn">zodResolver</span>(loginSchema),
  defaultValues: loginDefaults,
  mode:          <span class="str">"onBlur"</span>, <span class="cm">// validate when the user leaves a field</span>
});</pre>

<hr>

<h2>The Forms</h2>

<p>The form components are thin. They handle form state and call the mutation. All error display is delegated to shared components.</p>

<h3>LoginForm</h3>

<pre><span class="kw">export function</span> <span class="fn">LoginForm</span>() {
  <span class="kw">const</span> { register, handleSubmit, formState: { errors, isSubmitting }, setError }
    = <span class="fn">useForm</span>({ resolver: <span class="fn">zodResolver</span>(loginSchema), defaultValues: loginDefaults, mode: <span class="str">"onBlur"</span> });

  <span class="kw">const</span> { mutateAsync, isPending, error: serverError } = <span class="fn">useLogin</span>();
  <span class="kw">const</span> disabled = isSubmitting || isPending;

  <span class="kw">const</span> onSubmit = <span class="kw">async</span> (values) =&gt; {
    <span class="kw">try</span> {
      <span class="kw">await</span> <span class="fn">mutateAsync</span>(values);
    } <span class="kw">catch</span> (error) {
      <span class="fn">applyServerErrors</span>(error, setError);
    }
  };

  <span class="kw">return</span> (
    &lt;form onSubmit={<span class="fn">handleSubmit</span>(onSubmit)} noValidate&gt;
      &lt;<span class="tp">ServerErrorAlert</span> showFieldList error={serverError} /&gt;
      &lt;fieldset disabled={disabled}&gt;
        &lt;<span class="tp">InputField</span> name=<span class="str">"email"</span>    type=<span class="str">"email"</span>    label=<span class="str">"Email"</span>    register={register} error={errors.email?.message} /&gt;
        &lt;<span class="tp">InputField</span> name=<span class="str">"password"</span> type=<span class="str">"password"</span> label=<span class="str">"Password"</span> register={register} error={errors.password?.message} /&gt;
        &lt;<span class="tp">Button</span> type=<span class="str">"submit"</span> loading={disabled} disabled={disabled}&gt;Log in&lt;/<span class="tp">Button</span>&gt;
      &lt;/fieldset&gt;
    &lt;/form&gt;
  );
}</pre>

<h3>SignupForm</h3>

<pre><span class="kw">export function</span> <span class="fn">SignupForm</span>() {
  <span class="kw">const</span> { register, handleSubmit, formState: { errors, isSubmitting }, setError }
    = <span class="fn">useForm</span>({ resolver: <span class="fn">zodResolver</span>(signupSchema), defaultValues: signupDefaults, mode: <span class="str">"onBlur"</span> });

  <span class="kw">const</span> { mutateAsync, isPending, error } = <span class="fn">useSignup</span>();
  <span class="kw">const</span> disabled = isSubmitting || isPending;

  <span class="kw">const</span> onSubmit = <span class="kw">async</span> (values) =&gt; {
    <span class="kw">try</span> {
      <span class="cm">// acceptTerms is UI-only. Strip it before sending to the API.</span>
      <span class="kw">const</span> { acceptTerms: _omit, ...payload } = values;
      <span class="kw">await</span> <span class="fn">mutateAsync</span>(payload);
    } <span class="kw">catch</span> (error) {
      <span class="fn">applyServerErrors</span>(error, setError);
    }
  };

  <span class="kw">return</span> (
    &lt;form onSubmit={<span class="fn">handleSubmit</span>(onSubmit)} noValidate&gt;
      &lt;<span class="tp">ServerErrorAlert</span> showFieldList error={error} /&gt;
      &lt;fieldset disabled={disabled}&gt;
        &lt;<span class="tp">InputField</span> name=<span class="str">"firstName"</span>   label=<span class="str">"First Name"</span>  register={register} error={errors.firstName?.message} /&gt;
        &lt;<span class="tp">InputField</span> name=<span class="str">"lastName"</span>    label=<span class="str">"Last Name"</span>   register={register} error={errors.lastName?.message} /&gt;
        &lt;<span class="tp">InputField</span> name=<span class="str">"email"</span>       type=<span class="str">"email"</span>      label=<span class="str">"Email"</span>      register={register} error={errors.email?.message} /&gt;
        &lt;<span class="tp">InputField</span> name=<span class="str">"password"</span>    type=<span class="str">"password"</span>   label=<span class="str">"Password"</span>   register={register} error={errors.password?.message} /&gt;
        &lt;<span class="tp">CheckboxField</span> name=<span class="str">"acceptTerms"</span> label=<span class="str">"Accept Terms"</span> register={register} error={errors.acceptTerms?.message} /&gt;
        &lt;<span class="tp">Button</span> type=<span class="str">"submit"</span> loading={disabled}&gt;Create Account&lt;/<span class="tp">Button</span>&gt;
      &lt;/fieldset&gt;
    &lt;/form&gt;
  );
}</pre>

<p>Notice the <code>acceptTerms</code> field. It is validated by Zod on the client (the user must tick the box) but stripped from the payload before calling the API. The backend does not need it. Validate more on the client than you send to the server.</p>

<hr>

<h2>The Cooldown System for Rate-Limited Actions</h2>

<p>Some actions, like resending a verification email, should be rate-limited in the UI. The cooldown needs to survive a page reload.</p>

<p>The key insight: store the <em>timestamp of the last action</em> in localStorage, not the countdown value itself. Every render recalculates the remaining seconds from that timestamp. If the user closes the tab and returns two minutes later, the countdown picks up correctly.</p>

<pre><span class="kw">export function</span> <span class="fn">useCooldownTimer</span>({ storageKey, cooldownMs, cooldownSeconds }) {
  <span class="kw">const</span> [{ secondsLeft, isReady }, setTimerState] = <span class="fn">useState</span>({ secondsLeft: 0, isReady: <span class="kw">false</span> });

  <span class="kw">const</span> getSecondsLeft = <span class="fn">useCallback</span>(() =&gt; {
    <span class="kw">const</span> raw = localStorage.<span class="fn">getItem</span>(storageKey);
    <span class="kw">if</span> (!raw) <span class="kw">return</span> 0;
    <span class="kw">const</span> remaining = cooldownMs - (<span class="tp">Date</span>.<span class="fn">now</span>() - <span class="tp">Number</span>(raw));
    <span class="kw">return</span> remaining &gt; 0 ? <span class="tp">Math</span>.<span class="fn">ceil</span>(remaining / 1000) : 0;
  }, [storageKey, cooldownMs]);

  <span class="cm">// Read from localStorage only after hydration to avoid SSR mismatch</span>
  useIsomorphicLayoutEffect(() =&gt; {
    setTimerState({ secondsLeft: <span class="fn">getSecondsLeft</span>(), isReady: <span class="kw">true</span> });
  }, [getSecondsLeft]);

  <span class="cm">// Count down by one second at a time</span>
  <span class="fn">useEffect</span>(() =&gt; {
    <span class="kw">if</span> (!isReady || secondsLeft &lt;= 0) <span class="kw">return</span>;
    <span class="kw">const</span> id = <span class="fn">setTimeout</span>(() =&gt; {
      setTimerState((prev) =&gt; ({ ...prev, secondsLeft: <span class="fn">getSecondsLeft</span>() }));
    }, 1000);
    <span class="kw">return</span> () =&gt; <span class="fn">clearTimeout</span>(id);
  }, [isReady, secondsLeft, getSecondsLeft]);

  <span class="kw">const</span> triggerCooldown = <span class="fn">useCallback</span>(() =&gt; {
    localStorage.<span class="fn">setItem</span>(storageKey, <span class="tp">String</span>(<span class="tp">Date</span>.<span class="fn">now</span>()));
    setTimerState((prev) =&gt; ({ ...prev, secondsLeft: cooldownSeconds }));
  }, [storageKey, cooldownSeconds]);

  <span class="kw">return</span> { secondsLeft, canAct: isReady &amp;&amp; secondsLeft === 0, isReady, triggerCooldown };
}</pre>

<p>The <code>isReady</code> flag prevents an SSR hydration mismatch. On the server, localStorage does not exist, so <code>secondsLeft</code> starts at 0. On the client it might be non-zero. By delaying the localStorage read until after hydration with <code>useLayoutEffect</code>, the initial render is always consistent between server and client.</p>

<hr>

<h2>The Global Session Guard</h2>

<p>When a session fully expires (both tokens are dead), any query that fires will receive a 401 back from the proxy. TanStack Query's <code>QueryCache</code> has a global error handler that catches this and redirects the user:</p>

<pre><span class="kw">function</span> <span class="fn">makeQueryClient</span>() {
  <span class="kw">return new</span> <span class="tp">QueryClient</span>({
    queryCache: <span class="kw">new</span> <span class="tp">QueryCache</span>({
      onError: (error) =&gt; {
        <span class="kw">if</span> (error?.status === 401 &amp;&amp; <span class="kw">typeof</span> window !== <span class="str">"undefined"</span>) {
          window.location.<span class="fn">replace</span>(<span class="str">"/login"</span>);
        }
      },
    }),
    defaultOptions: queryConfig,
  });
}</pre>

<p>By the time this fires, the proxy has already tried to rotate the token and failed. This 401 is the true "session is dead" signal. Using <code>window.location.replace</code> instead of the Next.js router does a full page navigation, which clears all React state and ensures nothing stale carries over into the next session.</p>

<hr>

<h2>Complete Flow Walkthroughs</h2>

<h3>Signup</h3>
<div class="flow-diagram">
User fills SignupForm<br>
-&gt; Zod validates all fields (firstName, lastName, email, password, acceptTerms)<br>
-&gt; onSubmit strips acceptTerms from payload<br>
-&gt; useSignup().mutateAsync(payload)<br>
-&gt; signup() service -&gt; POST /api/proxy/api/v1/auth/signup<br>
-&gt; BFF proxy: no special handling, falls through to proxyRequest without auth headers<br>
-&gt; Real API creates account -&gt; 201 response<br>
-&gt; useSignup.onSuccess:<br>
&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;toastSuccess("Account created!")<br>
&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;localStorage.setItem("app_verify_cooldown", Date.now())<br>
&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;router.replace("/verify-email?email=encoded@email.com")
</div>

<h3>Email Verification</h3>
<div class="flow-diagram">
User arrives at /verify-email?email=... (no token yet) -&gt; page shows "check your inbox" UI<br>
<br>
User clicks link in email -&gt; lands at /verify-email?token=abc123&amp;email=...<br>
-&gt; VerifyEmailForm reads token from URL via useSearchParams()<br>
-&gt; useEffect fires once on mount (useRef guard prevents double-invoke in StrictMode)<br>
-&gt; useVerifyEmail().mutate({ token })<br>
-&gt; verifyEmail() service -&gt; POST /api/proxy/api/v1/auth/verify-email<br>
-&gt; BFF proxy detects VERIFY_EMAIL path -&gt; calls openSession()<br>
-&gt; Real API validates token -&gt; 200 OK + { accessToken, refreshToken }<br>
-&gt; BFF writes both tokens to httpOnly cookies<br>
-&gt; BFF returns { ok: true } to browser (no tokens in response body)<br>
-&gt; useVerifyEmail.onSuccess -&gt; router.replace("/") -&gt; user is now authenticated
</div>

<h3>Login</h3>
<div class="flow-diagram">
User fills LoginForm<br>
-&gt; Zod validates (email, password)<br>
-&gt; useLogin().mutateAsync({ email, password })<br>
-&gt; login() service -&gt; POST /api/proxy/api/v1/auth/login<br>
-&gt; BFF proxy detects LOGIN path -&gt; calls openSession()<br>
-&gt; Real API authenticates -&gt; 200 OK + tokens<br>
-&gt; BFF writes httpOnly cookies -&gt; returns { ok: true }<br>
-&gt; useLogin.onSuccess:<br>
&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;toastSuccess("Welcome back!")<br>
&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;qc.removeQueries([me]) -- clears any stale user cache<br>
&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;router.refresh() -- re-runs server components with new cookie context<br>
&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;router.replace("/") -- go to dashboard
</div>

<h3>Authenticated API Request With Silent Token Refresh</h3>
<div class="flow-diagram">
Any authenticated request fires from the browser<br>
-&gt; $apiClient -&gt; POST /api/proxy/...<br>
-&gt; BFF proxy.proxyRequest()<br>
-&gt; readAccessToken() from httpOnly cookie<br>
-&gt; $apiServer(path, { accessToken }) -&gt; Real API<br>
<br>
Path A - happy path:<br>
&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;200 OK -&gt; resolveWith(result) -&gt; data reaches the browser<br>
<br>
Path B - access token expired (401):<br>
&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;-&gt; rotateTokens() (singleton: only 1 refresh call runs even if 3 tabs get 401 at once)<br>
&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;-&gt; $apiServer(REFRESH, { refreshToken }) -&gt; new tokens<br>
&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;-&gt; writeSessionCookies(new tokens)<br>
&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;-&gt; retry original request with fresh accessToken<br>
&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;-&gt; 200 OK -&gt; browser gets data as if nothing happened<br>
<br>
Path C - refresh token also expired:<br>
&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;-&gt; clearSessionCookies()<br>
&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;-&gt; return 401 to browser<br>
&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;-&gt; TanStack QueryCache.onError -&gt; window.location.replace("/login")
</div>

<h3>Logout</h3>
<div class="flow-diagram">
User clicks logout<br>
-&gt; useLogout().mutate()<br>
-&gt; logout() service -&gt; POST /api/proxy/api/v1/auth/logout<br>
-&gt; BFF proxy detects LOGOUT path -&gt; calls closeSession()<br>
-&gt; readRefreshToken() -&gt; $apiServer(LOGOUT, { refreshToken }) -- tells backend to invalidate it<br>
-&gt; clearSessionCookies() -- always runs regardless of API response<br>
-&gt; useLogout.onSettled (runs whether success or failure):<br>
&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;qc.clear() -- wipe all cached data<br>
&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;router.refresh() -- server components now see no cookies<br>
&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;router.replace("/login")
</div>

<hr>

<h2>Key Design Decisions</h2>

<table style="border-collapse:collapse; width:100%; margin:10pt 0;">
  <tr>
    <th style="background:#0f3460; color:#fff; padding:7pt 10pt; text-align:left; font-family:Calibri,sans-serif; font-size:10pt;">Decision</th>
    <th style="background:#0f3460; color:#fff; padding:7pt 10pt; text-align:left; font-family:Calibri,sans-serif; font-size:10pt;">The reason</th>
  </tr>
  <tr>
    <td style="padding:7pt 10pt; border:1pt solid #e2e8f0; font-size:10.5pt;"><strong>httpOnly cookies for tokens</strong></td>
    <td style="padding:7pt 10pt; border:1pt solid #e2e8f0; font-size:10.5pt;">JavaScript cannot read httpOnly cookies. XSS attacks cannot steal what they cannot access. localStorage has no such protection.</td>
  </tr>
  <tr style="background:#f8fafc;">
    <td style="padding:7pt 10pt; border:1pt solid #e2e8f0; font-size:10.5pt;"><strong>BFF proxy for all API calls</strong></td>
    <td style="padding:7pt 10pt; border:1pt solid #e2e8f0; font-size:10.5pt;">The real API URL stays hidden from the browser. Token rotation happens server-side. One file handles all auth header logic.</td>
  </tr>
  <tr>
    <td style="padding:7pt 10pt; border:1pt solid #e2e8f0; font-size:10.5pt;"><strong>Custom CSRF header</strong></td>
    <td style="padding:7pt 10pt; border:1pt solid #e2e8f0; font-size:10.5pt;">Browsers block cross-origin requests from setting custom headers. Checking for <code>x-csrf: 1</code> is lightweight, reliable CSRF protection without token forms.</td>
  </tr>
  <tr style="background:#f8fafc;">
    <td style="padding:7pt 10pt; border:1pt solid #e2e8f0; font-size:10.5pt;"><strong>TanStack Query for auth state</strong></td>
    <td style="padding:7pt 10pt; border:1pt solid #e2e8f0; font-size:10.5pt;">User data is server state. TanStack Query handles caching, background re-fetches, and stale-time checks without a custom store.</td>
  </tr>
  <tr>
    <td style="padding:7pt 10pt; border:1pt solid #e2e8f0; font-size:10.5pt;"><strong>Token rotation deduplication</strong></td>
    <td style="padding:7pt 10pt; border:1pt solid #e2e8f0; font-size:10.5pt;">Multiple parallel requests can all get a 401 at the same time. Without deduplication, all of them fire a refresh request and all but the first fail. The singleton Promise pattern fixes this.</td>
  </tr>
  <tr style="background:#f8fafc;">
    <td style="padding:7pt 10pt; border:1pt solid #e2e8f0; font-size:10.5pt;"><strong>onSettled for logout</strong></td>
    <td style="padding:7pt 10pt; border:1pt solid #e2e8f0; font-size:10.5pt;">Logout cleanup should always happen, even if the API call fails. onSettled runs on success and failure. onSuccess alone would leave users stuck if the network was down.</td>
  </tr>
  <tr>
    <td style="padding:7pt 10pt; border:1pt solid #e2e8f0; font-size:10.5pt;"><strong>localStorage for cooldown timers</strong></td>
    <td style="padding:7pt 10pt; border:1pt solid #e2e8f0; font-size:10.5pt;">Storing a timestamp instead of a countdown means the timer survives page reloads and tab closes. The remaining time is always calculated fresh from the stored timestamp.</td>
  </tr>
  <tr style="background:#f8fafc;">
    <td style="padding:7pt 10pt; border:1pt solid #e2e8f0; font-size:10.5pt;"><strong>acceptTerms stripped before API call</strong></td>
    <td style="padding:7pt 10pt; border:1pt solid #e2e8f0; font-size:10.5pt;">UI-only fields should never be sent to the API. Validate them client-side with Zod, then strip them in onSubmit before calling the service.</td>
  </tr>
</table>

<hr>

<h2>Wrapping Up</h2>

<p>Here is the whole system in one paragraph:</p>

<p>
The browser talks only to a BFF proxy route. The proxy validates the CSRF header, writes JWTs to httpOnly cookies that JavaScript cannot touch, silently rotates tokens on 401 with a single-flight deduplication guard, and clears cookies on logout regardless of whether the API call succeeds. The service layer is pure functions with no UI logic. TanStack Query hooks own the side effects: toasts, redirects, and cache invalidation. Zod validates every form before anything hits the network. Server-side field errors are mapped back onto form fields automatically. Cooldown timers persist via localStorage without causing SSR hydration mismatches.
</p>

<p>
None of these individual patterns are new. The value is in how they fit together, each layer doing exactly one job and nothing more. You can take this entire approach and apply it to any Next.js 15 app. Swap the endpoint names, rename the constants, and you have a production-ready auth system.
</p>

<hr>
<p style="font-size:10pt; color:#94a3b8; font-style:italic;">
  If this was useful, share it with someone who is currently building auth from scratch. I write about real-world frontend engineering decisions based on production systems.
</p>

</body>
</html>
